"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:71:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/3-tips-to-make-your-site-more-accessible/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 05 Jul 2018 17:28:19 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Articles\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Accessibility\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1567699\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:603:\"<p>Access to the internet is often described as a basic human right. In an ideal world, persons of all abilities, languages, incomes, locations, and ages will be able to comfortably use the Web and all it has to offer. “Accessibility” is the term used to describe this project of making websites more inclusive—a big project, to&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/3-tips-to-make-your-site-more-accessible/\">3 Tips to Make Your Site More Accessible</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"George\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6553:\"<p><strong>Access to the internet is often described as a <a href=\"https://www.un.org/development/desa/disabilities/convention-on-the-rights-of-persons-with-disabilities/article-9-accessibility.html\">basic human right</a>. </strong>In an ideal world, persons of all abilities, languages, incomes, locations, and ages will be able to comfortably use the Web and all it has to offer.</p>\n<p>“Accessibility” is the term used to describe this project of making websites more inclusive—a big project, to be sure, but the good news is <strong>that accessibility is a spectrum.</strong> Your site doesn’t have to be perfectly accessible right now—just making it <em>a bit more accessible than it currently is</em> can be a huge improvement. We&#8217;ve compiled three tips to help you do just that.</p>\n<h2>Start Using Alt Text</h2>\n<p>People with visual impairments often interact with web pages through screen readers—devices that read the contents of a webpage out loud. When a <strong>screen reader comes across an image, the device will read the alt text aloud to describe what the individual is unable to see themselves.</strong></p>\n<p>Having good alt text on images truly enhances the experience of the web page for visually impaired users and it’s easy to do on your site. With WordPress, for example, <strong>you don’t have to know any code to ensure your images have alt text</strong>.</p>\n<p>When you view a single image in the WordPress Media Library, you’ll notice a field labeled “Alt text.” As its name implies, the contents of this field will be used as the image’s alt text.</p>\n<div id=\"attachment_1567702\" style=\"width: 2009px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1.png\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1567702\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1.png\" alt=\"The Alt Text Field in WordPress\" width=\"1999\" height=\"1236\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1.png 1999w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-137x85.png 137w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-300x185.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-768x475.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-665x411.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-430x266.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-645x399.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-1068x660.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-460x284.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-600x371.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/07/image1-500x309.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1999px) 100vw, 1999px\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">The alt text field in the WordPress media uploader.</p></div>\n<p>You can use this field to enter very simple descriptions of your image so the screen reader can read it out loud.</p>\n<p>There is one important exception to note: If an image is <em>purely</em> decorative and is not important to understanding the page’s content, <a href=\"https://www.w3.org/WAI/test-evaluate/preliminary/#images\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">you should just leave the alt text empty</a>.</p>\n<h2>Use Good Headings and Page Titles</h2>\n<p>Screen readers and other assistive devices rely on headings and page titles to help their users know <strong>what page they’re viewing and where they are in that page</strong>. That’s why it’s important to:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Make sure your headings <em>look</em> like headings—they should be larger than the body text, perhaps bold, perhaps darker than other text, etc.</li>\n<li>Make sure there’s a logical and consistent hierarchy of headings throughout your content. If your blog post titles use H1 tags, then any headers <em>within</em> the blog posts (e.g. section headers) should use H2 tags or lower.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>Now for page titles—when a browser tab is opened, the page title is the text used on the tab. <strong>Page titles need to be well-formatted and descriptive</strong> to accurately convey the page topic, as well as the website where it’s published.</p>\n<p>Take this blog post for example. The headline you see above is “3 Tips to Make Your Site More Accessible.” A good page title for this would be “3 Tips to Make Your Site More Accessible | The Events Calendar.” This simple, succinct, and useful title identifies both the page and website in one go.</p>\n<h2>Stress-Test Your Font Sizes</h2>\n<p>Let’s assume the typography on your site already looks great on mobile phones, tablets, and laptops—nice! But what happens if you increase the device screen font size settings by 30%?</p>\n<p>Many folks need to increase font sizes on their web browser and devices to make content easier to read. If larger font sizes break your design, you may need to enlist the help of a designer or developer to help fix it. Put in a bit of time to check this and <strong>make sure your content is still readable when font sizes are significantly increased.</strong></p>\n<h2>Other Considerations</h2>\n<p>The tips we’ve focused on here happen to deal with screen readers and visual impairment, but don’t forget that accessibility is about so much more.</p>\n<p>Additional considerations:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Audio and video: Consider offering transcripts for listeners with hearing impairments.</li>\n<li>Multilingual site users: Try using translation services or plugins to display your content in multiple languages.</li>\n<li>Page speed: Put some time and effort into optimizing load times on your site. This will benefit your bottom line and also ensure that people accessing your site on low-quality internet connections don’t have to wait an especially long time for your pages to load.</li>\n</ul>\n<hr style=\"width: 70%; margin-left: 15%; margin-right: 15%;\" />\n<p>Whether you’re making tweaks to an existing website or building a new site from scratch, these tips will help improve usability for all of your visitors, regardless of ability or disability. <strong>When sites and software are made with accessibility in mind, everybody wins. </strong></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/3-tips-to-make-your-site-more-accessible/\">3 Tips to Make Your Site More Accessible</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:1;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:55:\"Support Webinar: Customizations with Template Overrides\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:85:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/support-webinar-customizations-with-template-overrides/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 03 Jul 2018 14:53:22 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Tutorial\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1547860\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:602:\"<p>The first in a series of webinars by the Modern Tribe Support Team to help our users get the most out of our plugins, this webinar focuses on the popular topic of making customizations to event views. We’ve done our best to set things up to be highly customizable. In addition to actions and filters,&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/support-webinar-customizations-with-template-overrides/\">Support Webinar: Customizations with Template Overrides</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Jennifer\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:2899:\"<p>The first in a series of webinars by the Modern Tribe Support Team to help our users get the most out of our plugins, this webinar focuses on the popular topic of making customizations to event views.</p>\n<p>We’ve done our best to set things up to be highly customizable. In addition to actions and filters, you also have the option of overriding our front-end templates with your own from your child theme, where your changes will be safe from future updates. During the webinar, we review the steps for how to locate the correct files, copy them into your theme, and make a few changes. We also cover what can and cannot be customized with this method and provide some tips on resolving potential issues that you may encounter when doing template overrides. Finally, we wrap up our session by answering user questions.</p>\n<p>Before watching the webinar, we recommend taking a look at our Knowledgebase article on this topic, which will help you to get familiar with how this process works before we walk through it: <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/themers-guide\">https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/themers-guide</a></p>\n<h3>Watch the Webinar</h3>\n<p><iframe src=\"https://www.youtube.com/embed/E1roC_ysI-U\" width=\"560\" height=\"315\" frameborder=\"0\" allowfullscreen=\"allowfullscreen\"></iframe></p>\n<p>Be sure to subscribe to our Support Team&#8217;s brand new <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCtQYgMyJ9gSOD0NOsSNrMMA?sub_confirmation=1\">YouTube channel</a> to be the first to hear about upcoming support-related content!</p>\n<h3>Related Articles</h3>\n<p>There were a few things we mentioned that we weren&#8217;t able to dive into fully during the webinar, but here are some links that should help you get a handle on these topics:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/FTP_Clients\">Locating and editing site files</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Child_Themes\">Using a child theme</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.wpbeginner.com/plugins/how-to-easily-add-custom-css-to-your-wordpress-site/\">Custom CSS</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://codex.wordpress.org/Plugin_API#Hooks:_Actions_and_Filters\">WordPress hooks: actions and filters</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>We also have a few Knowledgebase articles that might help you out:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase-category/customizing/\">Customizing Our Plugins</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/tips-working-wordpress-actions-filters/\">Tribe Actions and Filters</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/functions/\">Tribe Functions</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/support-webinar-customizations-with-template-overrides/\">Support Webinar: Customizations with Template Overrides</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:2;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:32:\"Announcing Event Tickets 4.7.4.1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:63:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/announcing-event-tickets-4-7-4-1/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 22 Jun 2018 18:31:09 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Release Notes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1559476\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:589:\"<p>We&#8217;re pleased to announce that Event Tickets 4.7.4.1 is now available. In most cases you will be able to take advantage of automated updates, but if those are unavailable for any reason you can grab the release here and then update manually. Fix &#8211; Sending the ticket email when WooCommerce is active and purchasing another&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/announcing-event-tickets-4-7-4-1/\">Announcing Event Tickets 4.7.4.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Victor\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1062:\"<p>We&#8217;re pleased to announce that Event Tickets 4.7.4.1 is now available.</p>\n<p>In most cases you will be able to take advantage of automated updates, but if those are unavailable for any reason you can grab the <a href=\"https://downloads.wordpress.org/plugin/event-tickets.4.7.4.1.zip\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">release here</a> and then <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/manual-updates/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">update manually</a>.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Sending the ticket email when WooCommerce is active and purchasing another ticket type</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Thanks for your patience and support while we worked on this issue <img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/2.4/72x72/1f642.png\" alt=\"?\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/announcing-event-tickets-4-7-4-1/\">Announcing Event Tickets 4.7.4.1</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:3;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"Maintenance Release for the Week of 17 June 2018\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:68:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/maintenance-release-week-17-june-2018/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Wed, 20 Jun 2018 14:58:17 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Release Notes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1556953\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:616:\"<p>Welcome to maintenance release number 9 of 2018! If this is your first time getting an update from us, maintenance releases are smaller updates between major releases, and are mostly comprised of bug fixes, tweaks, and small (but meaningful!) improvements. We always recommend using a staging site to test these changes before updating on a&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/maintenance-release-week-17-june-2018/\">Maintenance Release for the Week of 17 June 2018</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Victor\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:10657:\"<p>Welcome to maintenance release number 9 of 2018! If this is your first time getting an update from us, maintenance releases are smaller updates between major releases, and are mostly comprised of bug fixes, tweaks, and small (but meaningful!) improvements. We always recommend using a <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/creating-using-wordpress-staging-site/\">staging site</a> to test these changes before updating on a live site.</p>\n<p>To see all of the changes included in this maintenance release, check out the changelogs for all updated plugins below:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#tec\">The Events Calendar 4.6.19</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#ep\">Events Calendar PRO 4.4.28</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#et\">Event Tickets 4.7.4</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#etp\">Event Tickets Plus 4.7.4</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#ebt\">Eventbrite Tickets 4.5.1</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#not-updated\">Not Updated this Release</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"tec\">The Events Calendar 4.6.19</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Feature</strong> &#8211; CSV importer now supports a featured event column</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> &#8211; Add Eventbrite Icon to Third Party Accounts on the help page</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: new title-bar template for loop views included above the filter bar and content containing the page title in a <samp>h1</samp> tag.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: adjust main content container element from <samp>div</samp> to <samp>main</samp>.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; More robust handling of errors and exceptions during Event Aggregator imports</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Ensure that the &#8220;Export Events&#8221; button is properly displayed in month view when paginating. Thanks to @linpleva, Steven, Will and others for flagging this!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Month view pagination for datepicker formats: YYYY.MM.DD, MM.DD.YYYY, and DD.MM.YYYY. Thanks @netzwerk, @wdburgdorf, @oliverwick and others for notifying us!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Resolved customizer inconsistencies with month/week views and full styles</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Check the Events Aggregator license each time the page is accessed</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Improve Event Import message responses from Event Aggregator for certain cases where &#8220;Unknown service message&#8221; would be returned</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Make the date picker respect the &#8220;Start of the week&#8221; Setting. Thanks to @websource, @dsb and others for flagging this!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Correct the &#8220;View All&#8221; link when using the events month view and plain permalinks. props to Kay and Robert for notifying us</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Keep filter bar date when changing from month to list view, with all datepicker formats. Thanks to Caio for reporting this!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Correct the pagination in list view when a keyword is being searched. Thanks to @versi, @akr and Mary for reporting this!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Split linked posts (Organizers and Venues) by ownership, for all users</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; The connected status for Eventbrite under Third Party Accounts on the Help page</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Fixed two PHP 5.2 errors on the Events &gt; Help page</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Display the correct Import Settings when Eventbrite Tickets is enabled</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Fixed a PHP warning related to the RSS feed in the Help page</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Add notices related to PHP minimum versions</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Modify the default values for the CSV settings if there&#8217;s no EA license</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Added classes to meta output in Single Event meta templates to facilitate customization</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Add the <samp>tribe_aggregator_async_insert_event</samp> filter to allow overriding the Event Aggregator asynchronous event insertion</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Add the <samp>&#8216;tribe_aggregator_async_import_event_task</samp> filter to allow overriding the Event Aggregator asynchronous import task</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Added venue google map link to events in Day view</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Renamed the Time zone mode option &#8220;Use the local time zones for each event&#8221; to &#8220;Use manual timezones for each event&#8221; (thanks @hikeitbaby for the suggestion)</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: heading hierarchy improvements throughout.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: make sure all elements have unique <samp>id</samp> attributes.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: remove redundant tab stops on feature image links.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: filter bar view selector adjustments.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: provide meaningful aria labels for filter bar inputs.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: hide Google Map embeds from screen readers.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Enable only url imports for Eventbrite when that plugin is not active</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; The EB 4.5 migration process to better detect events for migration and insure all fields are migrated</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Add <samp>tribe_events_month_has_events_filtered</samp> function and filter to see if there are events on a certain month, with filters (categories, search)</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 68 new strings added, 406 updated, 3 fuzzied, and 37 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"ep\">Events Calendar PRO 4.4.28</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> &#8211; accessibility repair: new title-bar template for loop views included above the filter bar and content containing the page title in a <samp>h1</samp> tag.</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Category Title in Photo View Loses Parameter After Navigating Previous/Next</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Make sure the recurring events series &#8220;after&#8221; field is not empty and a valid number. Thanks @versi for flagging this!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Resolved customizer inconsistencies with month/week views and full styles</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Resolved the datepicker losing state after visiting an event and hitting the &#8220;back&#8221; button on week view. Props to Joel for reporting!</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: heading hierarchy improvements throughout.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: make sure all elements have unique <samp>id</samp> attributes.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: remove redundant tab stops on feature image links.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Accessibility repair: hide Google Map embeds from screen readers.</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Added the unit to the distance output</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"et\">Event Tickets 4.7.4</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Properly calculate existing stock for RSVPs. Thanks to @afplct, @jacob, @dimaginet and others for flagging this!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Properly update attendees transient when checkin/unchekin an attendee, in order to see changes immediately. Thanks to @newcollegeofflorida and @gschnoor for flagging this!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Make sure the ticket creation is compatible with object cache. Thanks @zanart, @bethanymrac, @vividimage and others for flagging this!</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Display a notice if the user accesses the tickets page and doesn&#8217;t have tickets</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; If the ticket is a WooCommerce product and has a featured image, display it in the email</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Make sure the Paypal orders are being recorded. Thanks @burlingtonbytes for flagging this!</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Added new action, <samp>tribe_tickets_ticket_email_ticket_top</samp>, to the tickets email template</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Changed <samp>tribe_tickets_email_include_event_date</samp> filter default value to true. Now event date shows by default in RSVP ticket emails. Thanks @melvidge for the feedback</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Replaced start date in the RSVP non-attendace email template with full event schedule details</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Changed shortlinks to use https in Event Tickets welcome screen</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 2 new strings added, 66 updated, 0 fuzzied, and 1 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"etp\">Event Tickets Plus 4.7.4</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Fixed an issue with new &#8220;Enable QR codes for tickets?&#8221; option being only visible if WooCommerce was active</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 2 new strings added, 1 updated, 0 fuzzied, and 0 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"ebt\">Eventbrite Tickets 4.5.1</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> &#8211; A message before the Eventbrite metabox and hide the fields if there the app has not been authorized to import</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; The EB 4.5 migration process to better detect events for migration and insure all fields are migrated</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Only enable Live, Draft, and Canceled status for Eventbrite events</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Make the default selection of no for registering an event with Eventbrite</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Setup the text domain to enable translation of activation errors</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Discount link under Eventbrite Shortcuts</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 16 new strings added, 119 updated, 0 fuzzied, and 5 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"not-updated\">Not Updated this Release</h3>\n<p>The following plugins have not been updated this release, and will remain at the version numbers specified here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Community Events 4.5.12</li>\n<li>Filter Bar 4.5.6</li>\n<li>Community Tickets 4.5.4</li>\n<li>Image Widget 4.4.7</li>\n<li>Advanced Post Manager 4.4</li>\n<li>Image Widget Plus 1.0.2</li>\n<li>GigPress 2.3.20</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/maintenance-release-week-17-june-2018/\">Maintenance Release for the Week of 17 June 2018</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:4;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"PHP Version Requirement Changes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/php-version-requirement-changes/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Fri, 15 Jun 2018 15:07:32 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"News & Announcements\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1549542\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:542:\"<p>We have decided to change our minimum required PHP version from 5.2 to 5.6. This may sound like a big change for some, but don’t worry! We’ve got you covered, and can take you through the steps on how to make this change and quickly explain why this change is beneficial for all of us.&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/php-version-requirement-changes/\">PHP Version Requirement Changes</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5:\"Jaime\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:5942:\"<p><b>We have decided to change our minimum required PHP version from 5.2 to 5.6</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. This may sound like a big change for some, but don’t worry! We’ve got you covered, and can take you through the steps on how to make this change and quickly explain </span><i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">why</span></i><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> this change is beneficial for all of us.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">What is PHP?</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">In its simplest terms, PHP is the language that WordPress is written in. </span><b>The more recent the version of PHP your site runs, the faster and more secure it will be.</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> In fact, PHP versions below 5.6 generally don’t receive security updates, and are no longer maintained.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Why are we making this change?</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Using a more recent version of PHP will not only </span><b>help us build a better product</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">—it’ll also help to cut down on support time for outdated PHP versions. This change will furthermore create a better testing environment for us so that we can </span><b>get bug fixes out more efficiently</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">. These things, along with </span><b>improved security and performance</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, will benefit not only our team, but our users as well.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Who else has implemented this change?</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">WordPress.org itself now recommends upgrading to PHP version 7.2, as they outline in this article: </span><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/support/upgrade-php/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">https://wordpress.org/support/upgrade-php/</span></a></p>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">WooCommerce also recommends PHP version 7.0 or greater, </span><a href=\"https://docs.woocommerce.com/document/server-requirements/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">as stated on their website</span></a><b>.</b></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">When is this happening?</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If your site is running PHP version 5.5 or lower, you’ll begin to see an admin notice with our next maintenance release; this notice will serve as a gentle reminder that you should begin to consider updating, as we will begin to remove support for older versions of PHP in the near future.</span></p>\n<h2><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">How do I update my site’s PHP version?</span></h2>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">First, check which PHP version you are using. You can do this by going to Events Settings →  Help in your wp-admin and checking out your system information, like in the following screenshot:</span></p>\n<p><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-1549543\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-300x186.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"510\" height=\"316\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-300x186.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-137x85.png 137w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-768x477.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-665x413.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-430x267.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-645x401.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-460x286.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-600x373.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress-500x311.png 500w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/Help_‹_Test_Site_—_WordPress.png 842w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 510px) 100vw, 510px\" /></p>\n<p><b>If you’re using PHP version 5.5 or below,</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"> you’ll want to begin thinking about making this change. If your web host provides a cPanel for administering your site’s server, you can often find one-click installs of more recent PHP versions.</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br />\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><br />\n</span><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Otherwise, you can contact your host to make this switch easier. Usually all that’s required is a quick ping to their support team asking for a PHP version increase.</span></p>\n<p><b>If your host doesn’t have updated versions of PHP available</b><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">, we’d recommend switching to a host that does. We currently recommend the following hosts, which will make switching your PHP version easier:</span></p>\n<ul>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://mbsy.co/mtW6W\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Dreamhost</span></a></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://www.bigscoots.com/portal/?affid=687\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">BigScoots</span></a></li>\n<li style=\"font-weight: 400;\"><a href=\"https://inmotion-hosting.evyy.net/c/1249641/260033/4222\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">InMotion</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n<p><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">If you have any additional questions on this process, feel free to reach out to us over on the </span><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/help-desk/\"><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">Help Desk</span></a><span style=\"font-weight: 400;\">!</span></p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/php-version-requirement-changes/\">PHP Version Requirement Changes</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:5;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:36:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:37:\"Database Cleanup: Deleting Old Events\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:50:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/deleting-old-events/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Thu, 07 Jun 2018 14:06:45 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:2:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Articles\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:12:\"optimization\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1538046\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:572:\"<p>Deleting old events can be a cumbersome process, especially for online calendars that host hundreds or thousands of events. But it shouldn’t be, so that’s why we added new admin settings to make your life a whole lot easier. Why Delete Old Events? Although The Events Calendar is designed to handle both very high traffic&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/deleting-old-events/\">Database Cleanup: Deleting Old Events</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Jen Jamar\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3750:\"<p>Deleting old events can be a cumbersome process, especially for online calendars that host hundreds or thousands of events. But it shouldn’t be, so that’s why we added new admin settings to make your life a whole lot easier.</p>\n<h2>Why Delete Old Events?</h2>\n<p>Although <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-events-calendar/\">The Events Calendar</a> is designed to handle both very high traffic and large numbers of events, some performance factors are beyond our control.</p>\n<p>Just like regular blog posts, events are stored in your WordPress database. <strong>The more events displayed at once</strong>—whether on the front end or in the admin dashboard—<strong>the harder WordPress needs to work</strong>, increasing the likelihood you’ll see slowdowns on your site. And nobody wants to see that.</p>\n<h2>Automatically Delete Old Events</h2>\n<p>In version 4.6.13 of The Events Calendar, we introduced a setting that makes automatically deleting old events a breeze. Thanks to Patricia and our Community Team, you can quickly clean up outdated events on your calendar.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1538049\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting.png\" alt=\"Screenshot of settings to delete old events\" width=\"995\" height=\"497\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting.png 995w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-140x70.png 140w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-300x150.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-768x384.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-665x332.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-430x215.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-645x322.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-460x230.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-600x300.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/DeleteOldEventsSetting-500x250.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 995px) 100vw, 995px\" /></p>\n<p>To find the settings, head to Event Settings → General from your dashboard. There you’ll find options to move events to the trash or to permanently delete them. Once you’ve configured your settings, you can rest easy knowing <strong>past events will be automatically removed from your calendar</strong> without any additional input or effort on your part.</p>\n<h2>Increased Performance</h2>\n<p>Automatically deleting all events past a certain date frees up space in your database, which in turn increases the performance of your site.</p>\n<p><strong>Faster load time improves user experience, helps decrease bounce rates, increases conversions, and positively impacts your search ranking.</strong></p>\n<p>For more tips to keep your site running smoothly, check out our Knowledgebase articles on calendar optimization:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/performance-considerations/\">Calendar Performance Considerations</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/caching-basics/\">Caching Basics</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/extensions/recurring-event-cleanup-tool/\">Recurring Events Cleanup tool</a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/deleting-old-events/\">Database Cleanup: Deleting Old Events</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:6;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:48:\"Eventbrite Tickets: New &amp; Improved Features!\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:71:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/eventbrite-tickets-4-5-improved-features/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 04 Jun 2018 18:01:56 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:20:\"News & Announcements\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1543916\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:611:\"<p>The Eventbrite Tickets plugin you know and love just got a major update that includes a number of significant new features. Before we jump into all the features we added in version 4.5, there’s one super important thing to note: Eventbrite.com imports have moved from the old Legacy Imports section to the regular Imports section&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/eventbrite-tickets-4-5-improved-features/\">Eventbrite Tickets: New &#038; Improved Features!</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Jen Jamar\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:7877:\"<p>The Eventbrite Tickets plugin you know and love just got a major update that includes a number of significant new features.</p>\n<p>Before we jump into all the features we added in version 4.5, there’s <strong>one super important thing</strong> to note:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Eventbrite.com imports have moved from the old Legacy Imports section to the regular Imports section of your admin.</strong></p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><img class=\"alignleft wp-image-1544046 size-full\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin.png\" alt=\"Import origin screen\" width=\"1122\" height=\"389\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin.png 1122w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-140x49.png 140w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-300x104.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-768x266.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-665x231.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-1120x389.png 1120w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-430x149.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-645x224.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-1068x370.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-460x159.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-600x208.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/ImportOrigin-500x173.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1122px) 100vw, 1122px\" /></p>\n<p>You&#8217;ll find this screen in your admin under Events → Import</p>\n<p>By moving all import functionality to one central location, setting up new imports will be a smooth, straightforward process.</p>\n<h2>New Features and Functionality</h2>\n<p>Now onto the fun stuff—all the new features and functionality we&#8217;ve added to <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-eventbrite-tickets/\">Eventbrite Tickets</a>!</p>\n<p><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/product/wordpress-eventbrite-tickets/\"><img class=\"alignnone wp-image-1342645 size-large\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-665x299.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"665\" height=\"299\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-665x299.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-300x135.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-140x63.png 140w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-768x346.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-430x194.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-645x290.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-1068x481.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-460x207.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-600x270.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3-500x225.png 500w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2017/08/tec-eventbrite-3.png 1600w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 665px) 100vw, 665px\" /></a></p>\n<h3>Schedule Imports Automatically</h3>\n<p>Importing events from Eventbrite.com is now a whole lot easier in version 4.5. Scheduled imports keep your calendar full of new events. At the same time, you can fetch updates to previously-imported events so your WordPress calendar stays in sync with any changes made on Eventbrite.com.</p>\n<h3>Import by Location</h3>\n<p>Want to fill your calendar with local events? No problem! Simply input the Eventbrite.com location search URL to import events based on geographical location.</p>\n<p>Remember those scheduled imports we just mentioned? You can configure them so your site regularly pulls in new events in your area.</p>\n<h3>Focus on Favorite Organizers</h3>\n<p>In addition to location-based imports, you can also add events from specific Eventbrite.com organizer profiles.</p>\n<p>Pick your favorite, grab their organizer profile URL, and pop it into your Import dashboard. Boom! Now you’ve got an online calendar full of awesome events.</p>\n<h3>Preview Imports</h3>\n<p>As you start taking advantage of our new Eventbrite.com import features, you might be wondering what happens when you only want to import <em>some</em> of the events that are fetched instead of all of them.</p>\n<p>That’s where the new Preview button comes into play. Before the import runs, you’ll have a chance to preview the events and make sure they’re really the ones you want to add to your calendar. Go ahead and cherry pick to your heart’s content.</p>\n<p><img class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-1544050\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview.png\" alt=\"Import preview screen\" width=\"1102\" height=\"712\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview.png 1102w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-132x85.png 132w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-300x194.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-768x496.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-665x430.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-430x278.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-645x417.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-1068x690.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-460x297.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-600x388.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/06/EventbriteImportPreview-500x323.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1102px) 100vw, 1102px\" /></p>\n<h3>Assign Categories and Status</h3>\n<p>Categories are powerful for organizing events on your WordPress calendar. Whether you’re running scheduled imports or doing a one-time manual import, you&#8217;ll now have the option to apply a category to all events as they’re added to your calendar.</p>\n<p>The same goes for publishing status. For even more control over which events are published on your calendar, you can set them to Pending Review. If you already know they’re good to go, you can set them to Publish so that they&#8217;re publicly visible on your calendar as soon as they&#8217;re imported.</p>\n<h3>Manage Event Updates</h3>\n<p>Version 4.5 introduces Event Update Authority, a useful setting to manage how changes are applied during the import process.</p>\n<p>Let’s say you have a scheduled import to pull in new events from a specific Eventbrite.com organizer on a weekly basis. What happens when they make changes to an event you’ve already published on your calendar?</p>\n<p>With Event Update Authority, you get to decide if (and how) any changes are applied to your site.</p>\n<h2>Get Eventbrite Tickets 4.5 Now</h2>\n<p>If you haven’t updated to version 4.5 yet, check it out now by updating from your WordPress admin or by manually downloading it from your <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/my-account/downloads/\">My Account &gt; Downloads</a> page.</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/eventbrite-tickets-4-5-improved-features/\">Eventbrite Tickets: New &#038; Improved Features!</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:7;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:62:\"Release: The Events Calendar 4.6.18 and Eventbrite Tickets 4.5\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:92:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-the-events-calendar-4-6-18-and-eventbrite-tickets-4-5/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Mon, 04 Jun 2018 16:53:35 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Release Notes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1540298\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:665:\"<p>We’ve polished up Eventbrite Tickets and The Events Calendar! In this version we moved the Eventbrite Tickets import functionality from the Legacy Imports page to the Imports page (where the Event Aggregator magic happens). You will now have much more control when importing Eventbrite.com events into your site. Ready to explore the details of this&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-the-events-calendar-4-6-18-and-eventbrite-tickets-4-5/\">Release: The Events Calendar 4.6.18 and Eventbrite Tickets 4.5</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Victor\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:3556:\"<p>We’ve polished up Eventbrite Tickets and The Events Calendar! In this version we moved the Eventbrite Tickets import functionality from the Legacy Imports page to the Imports page (where the Event Aggregator magic happens). You will now have much more control when importing <a href=\"https://www.eventbrite.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Eventbrite.com</a> events into your site.</p>\n<p>Ready to explore the details of this release? On to the changelogs!</p>\n<h3>Changelogs</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#tec\">The Events Calendar 4.6.18</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#ebt\">Eventbrite Tickets 4.5</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"tec\">The Events Calendar 4.6.18</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Eventbrite to Event Aggregator import origins</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Priority attribute to Import Setting fields to be able to customize order of fields</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Default category and change authority for Eventbrite Imports</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Ability to schedule Eventbrite imports through Event Aggregator</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Preview for Eventbrite events in the import screen ordered from farthest future event to closest</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Import Eventbrite events using the Other URL import origin</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Ability to preview and import multiple Eventbrite events using the Organizer URL</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Import from Eventbrite Location Search URL, i.e. https://www.eventbrite.com/d/or&#8211;portland/events/</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> — Move Eventbrite settings from Legacy Import to Settings Import Tab</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> — Add Eventbrite imports to the Import History Tab</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> — Remove Legacy Imports UI</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"ebt\">Eventbrite Tickets 4.5</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Syncing of Eventbrite events updates to WordPress</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Move the Eventbrite imports to Event Aggregator service</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Migration from old Eventbrite Imports to new Event Aggregator standard</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Bulk imports from Eventbrite Profile</li>\n<li><strong>Add</strong> — Prompt on update or install to Eventbrite 4.5 to authorize Event Aggregator EB App</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> — Move Eventbrite settings from Legacy Import to Settings Import Tab</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> — Styling of the Eventbrite datepicker to match style of event datepicker</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> — EB tickets metabox to hide admin fields if you are not the owner of the event in Eventbrite</li>\n<li><strong>Deprecated</strong> &#8211; Eventbrite authorization interface with replace in Event Aggregator</li>\n<li><strong>Deprecated</strong> &#8211; Eventbrite API class including calls to <samp>tribe( &#8216;eventbrite.api&#8217; )</samp> use <samp>tribe( &#8216;eventbrite.sync.event&#8217; )</samp> or <samp>tribe( &#8216;eventbrite.sync.utilities&#8217; )</samp> instead</li>\n</ul>\n<hr />\n<p>Thanks for your continued support! We hope this update makes your sites much better, your jobs way easier, and your overall experience using our plugins a breeze. Cheers to you on behalf of everyone here at Modern Tribe!</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/release-the-events-calendar-4-6-18-and-eventbrite-tickets-4-5/\">Release: The Events Calendar 4.6.18 and Eventbrite Tickets 4.5</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:8;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:33:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:47:\"Maintenance Release for the Week of 27 May 2018\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:78:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/maintenance-release-for-the-week-of-27-may-2018/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 29 May 2018 18:07:33 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13:\"Release Notes\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1540756\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:627:\"<p>Welcome to the eighth maintenance release of 2018! If this is your first time getting an update from us, maintenance releases are smaller updates between major releases, and are mostly comprised of bug fixes, tweaks, and small (but meaningful!) improvements. We always recommend using a staging site to test these changes before updating on a&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/maintenance-release-for-the-week-of-27-may-2018/\">Maintenance Release for the Week of 27 May 2018</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"Victor\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8947:\"<p>Welcome to the eighth maintenance release of 2018! If this is your first time getting an update from us, <strong>maintenance releases are smaller updates between major releases</strong>, and are mostly comprised of bug fixes, tweaks, and small (but meaningful!) improvements. We always recommend using a <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/knowledgebase/creating-using-wordpress-staging-site/\">staging site</a> to <strong>test these changes before updating on a live site</strong>.</p>\n<p>To see all of the changes included in this maintenance release, check out the changelogs for all updated plugins below:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"#tec\">The Events Calendar 4.6.17</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#ep\">Events Calendar PRO 4.4.27</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#et\">Event Tickets 4.7.3</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#etp\">Event Tickets Plus 4.7.3</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#ce\">Community Events 4.5.12</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#fb\">Filter Bar 4.5.6</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#not-updated\">Not Updated this Release</a></li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"tec\">The Events Calendar 4.6.17</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Add tribe_redirected parameter to enable a visitor to select another view after default mobile redirect, thanks to Marcella for notifying us</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Hide any errors generated by servers that don&#8217;t support <samp>set_time_limit()</samp> (props to @jsww for flagging this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Add a warning when the site Timezone is set to UTC</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; An issue with organizers and venues not being attached to events on Eventbrite import</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Adjust the <samp>Tribe__PUE__Checker</samp> $stats creation regarding WordPress multisite installs</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 4 new strings added, 170 updated, 1 fuzzied, and 0 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"ep\">Events Calendar PRO 4.4.27</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Resolved problems with date parameter for the week view of <samp>[tribe_events]</samp></li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Ignore empty exclusions in recurring events</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Parsing of ordinals format in to the recurring section (thanks to Steve for reporting this problem!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Modify time-frame limitations to &#8220;Related Events&#8221; (props @cliffy, @coachsuper and others for flagging this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Add <samp>tribe_redirected</samp> parameter to enable a visitor to select another view after default mobile redirect, thanks to Marcella for notifying us</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Allow optionally showing the Before/After HTML from Event Settings on shortcode-generated calendars (thanks to Ria for reporting this problem in our Help Desk!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Hide any errors generated by servers that don&#8217;t support <samp>set_time_limit()</samp> (Thanks to Jörg for notifying us!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Ensured the &#8220;This Week&#8221; widget use the date display settings from the settings panel (props to Miguel and @wleideckw for reporting this problem!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Display the &#8220;loading wheel&#8221; when navigating events using <samp>[tribe_events]</samp> shortcode (Thanks to @atoohill for notifying us!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Prevent week view event links to require &#8220;double tap&#8221; on iPads (props to @sschuler for reporting this problem!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Add Filter Bar checkboxes compatibility (props @barberaprode-nl, @kentyn and others for flagging this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Correct behavior of State/Province field on Settings &gt; Default Content screen</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Replaced the address attribute with a street attribute in <samp>[tribe_events_list]</samp> shortcode and List Widget (Thanks to Sebastien for notifying us!)</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 7 new strings added, 126 updated, 1 fuzzied, and 3 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"et\">Event Tickets 4.7.3</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Display the correct number of attendees on the events list in the admin section (props to @vbt, @xen and others for flagging this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Display the correct number of available tickets on list and day view (Thanks to @designfestbrum, @kaisv and others for reporting this problem!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Ensured that the ticket start and end sale date respect the event timezone (props to @Ryan, @Georges, @bcbookprizes for flagging this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Add methods to handle refunds for tickets and fix the attendees report accordingly</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Modify the front end ticket list display so it always displays even when Hide From Event Listings is checked for an event, thanks to @atmedia for reporting</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Better handle the admin display of ticket prices that are affected WooCommerce Membership discounts (thanks to @cardinalacres, @steamfablab, and others for reporting these issues!)</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Added a &#8220;Return to Cart&#8221; link to PayPal tickets form</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Changed validation on the option &#8216;Post types that can have tickets&#8217; to allow empty value</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 10 new strings added, 170 updated, 1 fuzzied, and 3 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"etp\">Event Tickets Plus 4.7.3</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Make QR codes optional via new &#8220;Enable QR codes for tickets?&#8221; option in Tickets settings (applies to users of WooCommerce only at this time)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Remove attendees from the public list if their order have failed (Thanks @beerddwr for flagging this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Fixed an issue where EDD was throwing insufficient stock error for shared capacity tickets (props to @artstream8401 for reporting this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Clean the attendees cache every time an order is updated, so the changes are reflected immediately (Thanks @bartenderatlas, @artistinformatici, @danceworks and others for reporting!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Synchronize the event cost when a WooCommerce sale start or end (Thanks @floydcountrystore for notifying us!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Ensured that the tickets start and end sale date respect the event timezone (props @Ryan, @Georges and others for flagging this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Add class to handle WooCommerce order refunds on a ticket basis</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Prevent the event tickets page to break when EDD is deactivated and there were EDD orders</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Add default title to the ticket field set if none provided</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Sanitize HTML classes for ticket attendee details in the admin area (Thanks @Gergana, @ucheng and @mr-d for flagging this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Ignore whitespaces in ticket required fields (props @jonahgirl and @seanaguilar for notifying us!)</li>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Render ticket fields without label (Thanks @creeert-net and @daviddweb for spotting this!)</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Made the QR code base URL default to having a trailing slash to prevent issues with some server configurations</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Added new <samp>tribe_tickets_qr_code_base_url</samp> to allow easy filtering of the QR code base URL</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 5 new strings added, 74 updated, 0 fuzzied, and 1 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"ce\">Community Events 4.5.12</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Fix</strong> &#8211; Added method with <samp>tribe_community_events_max_file_size_allowed</samp> filter to set the max file size allowed</li>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Updated views: src/views/community/modules/image.php</li>\n<li><strong>Language</strong> &#8211; 0 new strings added, 8 updated, 0 fuzzied, and 0 obsoleted</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"fb\">Filter Bar 4.5.6</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Tweak</strong> &#8211; Added missing license.txt file</li>\n</ul>\n<h3 id=\"not-updated\">Not Updated this Release</h3>\n<p>The following plugins have not been updated this release, and will remain at the version numbers specified here:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Community Tickets 4.5.4</li>\n<li>Image Widget 4.4.7</li>\n<li>Advanced Post Manager 4.4</li>\n<li>Eventbrite Tickets 4.4.9</li>\n<li>Image Widget Plus 1.0.2</li>\n<li>GigPress 2.3.20</li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/maintenance-release-for-the-week-of-27-may-2018/\">Maintenance Release for the Week of 27 May 2018</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}i:9;a:6:{s:4:\"data\";s:39:\"\n		\n		\n		\n		\n				\n		\n		\n\n		\n		\n				\n			\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"child\";a:3:{s:0:\"\";a:6:{s:5:\"title\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:26:\"Going Gutenberg: Chapter V\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:56:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-v/\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:7:\"pubDate\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:31:\"Tue, 29 May 2018 16:14:56 +0000\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:8:\"category\";a:3:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:8:\"Articles\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:1;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:15:\"Going Gutenberg\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}i:2;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:9:\"Gutenberg\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:4:\"guid\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:40:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/?p=1538419\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:1:{s:11:\"isPermaLink\";s:5:\"false\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:11:\"description\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:567:\"<p>Going Gutenberg is an ongoing series about our process of integrating our products with the WordPress block editor. View all chapters in the series here, and be sure to follow us on Facebook or Twitter to never miss an update. In Going Gutenberg: Chapter IV we talked about thinking of blocks as having distinct “preview”&#8230;</p>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-v/\">Going Gutenberg: Chapter V</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:32:\"http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/\";a:1:{s:7:\"creator\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"George\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:40:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/\";a:1:{s:7:\"encoded\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:13919:\"<p><em>Going Gutenberg</em> is an ongoing series about our process of integrating our products with the WordPress block editor. View all chapters in the series <a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/tag/going-gutenberg/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">here</a>, and be sure to follow us on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/theeventscalendar\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Facebook</a> or <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TheEventsCal\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Twitter</a> to never miss an update.</p>\n<hr style=\"width: 70%; margin-left: 15%; margin-right: 15%;\" />\n<p>In <em><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-iv/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Going Gutenberg: Chapter IV</a></em> we talked about thinking of blocks as having distinct “preview” and “active” states, which helped us resolve a number of design challenges with our most intricate, data-heavy blocks.</p>\n<p>But a number of design challenges still remain. As we dig deeper into building the Event Price block, for example, <strong>even the notion of preview and active states doesn’t fully resolve all design problems</strong>. We’ve had to pause, think, and iterate some more to come up with a third concept to help with designing complex blocks: the “dashboard.”</p>\n<h2>The Concept of Block Dashboards</h2>\n<p>We’re not talking about the <em>WordPress</em> dashboard. We’re talking about “block dashboards,” a term we came up with to refer to pieces of the user interface (UI) that allow for the active state of a block to essentially have <em>its own</em> distinct active and preview states.</p>\n<h2>Block Dashboards in Action</h2>\n<p>Visual examples make this more concrete, so let’s start with some examples where block dashboards are <strong>not</strong> needed.</p>\n<p>Our <em>Event Sharing</em> block is so simple that it doesn’t need an active and preview state—the block closely resembles how it’ll look on the front end and requires such little configuration that the block is truly WYSIWYG:</p>\n<div id=\"attachment_1538423\" style=\"width: 1004px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-sharing-block.gif\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1538423\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-sharing-block.gif\" alt=\"The Event Sharing Block\" width=\"994\" height=\"572\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">A look at the Event Sharing block in action.</p></div>\n<p>In the example of our <em>Event Price</em> block, however, we see the value of having distinct active and preview states. Here’s the block’s preview state, which provides a close approximation of how it will appear on the front end:</p>\n<div id=\"attachment_1538426\" style=\"width: 2056px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview.png\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1538426\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview.png\" alt=\"The Event Price Block\'s Preview State\" width=\"2046\" height=\"1208\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview.png 2046w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-140x83.png 140w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-300x177.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-768x453.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-665x393.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-430x254.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-645x381.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-1068x631.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-460x272.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-600x354.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-cost-preview-500x295.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2046px) 100vw, 2046px\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">A look at the Event Price block in its preview state.</p></div>\n<p>Upon interacting with the block, it’s put into an active state—an expanded form UI that doesn’t look anything like the block’s front-end output, but allows for easier data entry:</p>\n<div id=\"attachment_1538427\" style=\"width: 2066px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active.png\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1538427\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active.png\" alt=\"The Event Price Block\'s Active State\" width=\"2056\" height=\"946\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active.png 2056w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-140x64.png 140w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-300x138.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-768x353.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-665x306.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-430x198.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-645x297.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-1068x491.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-460x212.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-600x276.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-price-active-500x230.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2056px) 100vw, 2056px\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">A look at the Event Price block in its active state.</p></div>\n<p>Now let’s turn to the <em>Date and Time</em> block. Here you can see its unassuming preview state:</p>\n<div id=\"attachment_1538428\" style=\"width: 2062px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview.png\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1538428\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview.png\" alt=\"The Date and Time Block\'s Preview State\" width=\"2052\" height=\"984\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview.png 2052w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-140x67.png 140w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-300x144.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-768x368.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-665x319.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-430x206.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-645x309.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-1068x512.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-460x221.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-600x288.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-preview-500x240.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2052px) 100vw, 2052px\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">A look at the event Date and Time block in its preview state.</p></div>\n<p>Upon interaction, you can see its active state:</p>\n<div id=\"attachment_1538429\" style=\"width: 2058px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active.png\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1538429\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active.png\" alt=\"The Date and Time Block\'s Active State\" width=\"2048\" height=\"1136\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active.png 2048w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-140x78.png 140w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-300x166.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-768x426.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-665x369.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-430x239.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-645x358.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-1068x592.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-460x255.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-600x333.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-active-500x277.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 2048px) 100vw, 2048px\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">A look at the event Date and Time block in its active state.</p></div>\n<p><em>Within</em> the active state, we see the dashboard concept in action. When you choose multiple dates, for example, much of the “active state” of the block changes. In the following screenshot, you can see how the display of the start and end dates differs from the screenshot above:</p>\n<div id=\"attachment_1538430\" style=\"width: 2009px\" class=\"wp-caption aligncenter\"><a href=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard.png\"><img class=\"size-full wp-image-1538430\" src=\"http://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard.png\" alt=\"The &quot;Dashoard&quot; Concept in Action in the Date and Time Block\" width=\"1999\" height=\"1150\" srcset=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard.png 1999w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-140x81.png 140w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-300x173.png 300w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-768x442.png 768w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-665x383.png 665w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-430x247.png 430w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-645x371.png 645w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-1068x614.png 1068w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-460x265.png 460w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-600x345.png 600w, https://theeventscalendar.com/content/uploads/2018/05/event-date-time-dashboard-500x288.png 500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1999px) 100vw, 1999px\" /></a><p class=\"wp-caption-text\">A look at how the Date and Time block&#8217;s active state is not *just* an active state; it employs the dashboard concept so that the active state has its own preview/active modes based on various types of interaction.</p></div>\n<p>The &#8220;dashboard&#8221; approach here means that aspects of the active state are only visible when necessary. This is a boon for usability because it lets us show elements of complicated forms only when they are essential, like the underlying active/preview state structure itself.</p>\n<h2>The Lifetime of Design Decisions</h2>\n<p>We shared in our previous chapter how thinking of blocks as having active and preview states helped us resolve a number of design challenges. In just a few short weeks or working down that path, we ran into the limitations of that concept and needed to expand on those ideas, arriving at the dashboard concept described here.</p>\n<p>As we keep designing complex blocks—and as WordPress Core’s block editor itself changes—we’ll almost certainly have to come up with new design approaches and philosophies that build on (and possibly even replace) our existing ones.</p>\n<p>What approaches have you taken in designing blocks (complex or otherwise)? Let us know on <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/theeventscalendar\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Facebook</a> or <a href=\"https://twitter.com/TheEventsCal\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Twitter.</a></p>\n<p>To stay up to date on our Gutenberg journey, be sure to <a href=\"https://confirmsubscription.com/h/r/F35BA2B75B521339\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">subscribe to this blog</a> so you never miss an update.</p>\n<hr style=\"width: 70%; margin-left: 15%; margin-right: 15%;\" />\n<p><img src=\"https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/2.4/72x72/1f514.png\" alt=\"?\" class=\"wp-smiley\" style=\"height: 1em; max-height: 1em;\" /> <strong>Please Note:</strong> This is a blog series about active development and exploration. Anything we mention here is subject to change, and this blog series should be read as a tentative roadmap for our products—not an official release plan.</p>\n<h3>Going Gutenberg Series</h3>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-i/\">Chapter I</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-ii/\">Chapter II</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-iii/\">Chapter III</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-iv/\">Chapter IV</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-v/\"><strong>Chapter V</strong></a></li>\n</ul>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com/going-gutenberg-chapter-v/\">Going Gutenberg: Chapter V</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://theeventscalendar.com\">The Events Calendar</a>.</p>\n\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}s:27:\"http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom\";a:1:{s:4:\"link\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:0:\"\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:1:{s:0:\"\";a:3:{s:4:\"href\";s:35:\"https://theeventscalendar.com/feed/\";s:3:\"rel\";s:4:\"self\";s:4:\"type\";s:19:\"application/rss+xml\";}}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}s:44:\"http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/syndication/\";a:2:{s:12:\"updatePeriod\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:6:\"hourly\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}s:15:\"updateFrequency\";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:\"data\";s:1:\"1\";s:7:\"attribs\";a:0:{}s:8:\"xml_base\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"xml_base_explicit\";b:0;s:8:\"xml_lang\";s:0:\"\";}}}}}}}}}}}}s:4:\"type\";i:128;s:7:\"headers\";O:42:\"Requests_Utility_CaseInsensitiveDictionary\":1:{s:7:\"\0*\0data\";a:10:{s:4:\"date\";s:29:\"Fri, 06 Jul 2018 03:16:28 GMT\";s:12:\"content-type\";s:34:\"application/rss+xml; charset=UTF-8\";s:6:\"server\";s:21:\"nginx/1.10.3 (Ubuntu)\";s:13:\"cache-control\";s:28:\"max-age=779, must-revalidate\";s:12:\"x-powered-by\";s:27:\"PHP/7.0.28-0ubuntu0.16.04.1\";s:4:\"vary\";s:6:\"Cookie\";s:13:\"last-modified\";s:29:\"Fri, 06 Jul 2018 02:28:59 GMT\";s:4:\"etag\";s:34:\"\"f9f64c660895b12afa482e9d7dbd5513\"\";s:12:\"x-robots-tag\";s:15:\"noindex, fo